"""
MKT Context Commentary — Mark chapters 7–8
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-mark-7-8.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/mark.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/mark.json (MKT text)

Key decisions in this range:
- Mark written for Roman Gentile audience (ca. 65-70 CE); explains Jewish purity customs in 7:3-4
- Corban (qorban) is a vow mechanism; m. Nedarim confirms its legal weight
- Mark 7:16 absent from best manuscripts (Sinaiticus, Vaticanus); brief note provided
- Mark's editorial note 7:19 ("declaring all foods clean") addresses Gentile Christian context
- Syrophoenician woman: "Greek" = Hellenis (Greek-speaking Gentile); kynaria = diminutive (puppies)
- Ephphatha preserved in Aramaic like talitha koum — Petrine eyewitness tradition
- Second feeding (ch.8) in Gentile Decapolis; seven baskets vs. twelve in first feeding
- Two-stage Bethsaida healing is unique; structured parallel to disciples' gradual understanding
- "Take up your cross" (8:34) had visceral concrete meaning for Roman audience familiar with crucifixions
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

MARK = {
  "7": {
    "2": '<p>Ritual hand-washing before meals (<em>netilat yadayim</em>) was a Pharisaic purity extension, not a biblical requirement. The Torah required priests to wash hands and feet before entering the sanctuary (Exod 30:19-21), but the Pharisees extended this priestly purity standard to all Jews before ordinary meals — one of many ways they democratized priestly holiness. "Defiled" translates <em>koinais</em> (common, ritually impure — the opposite of <em>hagios</em>, holy/set apart). The disciples\' failure to wash was not a hygiene violation but a failure to observe the oral Torah that the Pharisees treated as equally binding as the written Torah.</p>',
    "3": '<p>Mark\'s parenthetical explanation in vv.3-4 is directed entirely at his Gentile Roman audience: any Jewish reader would know these practices without explanation. The clarification that "all the Jews" observe hand-washing and that this derives from "the tradition of the elders" (oral Torah) signals Mark\'s explanatory mission for readers unfamiliar with Jewish domestic practice. This is one of several such editorial explanations in Mark (cf. 7:11 explaining corban; 14:12 explaining Passover preparation; 15:42 explaining the Preparation Day) — a consistent feature of the Roman audience context identified by Papias\'s description of Mark as Peter\'s interpreter.</p>',
    "4": '<p>Washing after coming from the marketplace reflects concern about contact with Gentiles whose impurity status was uncertain — even touching goods they had handled could be a source of ritual contamination in strict Pharisaic interpretation. The washing of "cups, pitchers, and kettles" reflects real Levitical concerns about vessel purity (Lev 11:32-33 distinguishes which vessels contract impurity and how they are cleansed; clay vessels that contact impurity must be broken; bronze vessels may be washed). Mark\'s mention of these details confirms his source\'s familiarity with actual Jewish practice even while writing for readers who need the explanation.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The question "Why don\'t your disciples live according to the tradition of the elders?" frames the dispute accurately: it is not a question about the written Torah (which Jesus and his disciples presumably honored) but about the oral Torah — the accumulated interpretive traditions that the Pharisees held to be equally binding. The phrase "tradition of the elders" (<em>paradosis tōn presbyterōn</em>) is the Pharisaic term for this body of law; it later became the basis for the Mishnah (codified ca. 200 CE). Jesus\'s response will distinguish between the divine authority of the written Torah and the merely human authority of its Pharisaic interpretation.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"Isaiah was right when he prophesied about you hypocrites" — the citation is from Isaiah 29:13, in the LXX form (which differs slightly from the MT in a way that sharpens the accusation). The Greek word <em>hypokritēs</em> originally meant "actor" in the theatrical sense — someone playing a role, presenting a face that does not correspond to inner reality. The Septuagintal version of Isaiah 29:13 that Jesus cites emphasizes the mismatch between external worship performance and the internal condition of the heart, making it a precise accusation: the purity traditions being enforced are external performances without corresponding interior reality.</p>',
    "7": '<p>"Their worship of me is in vain; their teachings are merely human rules" — the second line of the Isaiah citation introduces the key distinction Jesus will develop: God\'s commands vs. human traditions. The Isaiah prophecy was originally addressed to Jerusalem during a crisis of superficial religion — external observance maintained while the heart was far from God. Jesus applies it to a specific tradition (hand-washing) as an instance of the general pattern Isaiah identified: religion as performance of rules rather than response of the heart to God\'s actual commands.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"You have let go of the commands of God and are holding on to human traditions" — Jesus makes the structural diagnosis explicit. The oral Torah in its Pharisaic form had not merely supplemented the written Torah but, in specific cases like corban (vv.10-12), created mechanisms by which religious forms could be used to evade the written Torah\'s clear ethical demands. The Pharisees were not simply adding extras to an already sufficient law; they were generating a parallel system that could conflict with and override it. This is the charge that requires the corban example to make concrete.</p>',
    "9": '<p>"You have a fine way of setting aside the commands of God in order to observe your own traditions!" — the Greek <em>kalōs</em> (fine, well) is deeply ironic: not a compliment but a sardonic acknowledgment of their skill in doing exactly what they should not. The word <em>athetein</em> (set aside, nullify, reject) is a strong legal term for formal invalidation — they have effectively voided the written commandment in this area. The rhetorical move prepares for the specific case: the corban example is not an edge case but a demonstration of the systemic problem Jesus is identifying.</p>',
    "10": '<p>"For Moses said, \'Honor your father and mother\'" (Exod 20:12; Deut 5:16) and "Anyone who curses their father or mother is to be put to death" (Exod 21:17; Lev 20:9) — the two citations together establish that the written Torah not only commanded honoring parents positively (the fifth commandment) but also prescribed the death penalty for its violation at the extreme negative end. Jesus is citing the weightiest possible forms of the commandment — both the positive requirement and the capital sanction — to set up the contrast with what the oral tradition permitted through the corban mechanism.</p>',
    "11": '<p>Corban (<em>qorban</em>, from the Hebrew root meaning "to draw near" — an offering brought near to God) was a vow formula by which a person declared property to be dedicated to God. Once something was declared corban, it was legally unavailable for any other use, including being given to parents. The Mishnah (tractate <em>Nedarim</em> 3.2, 9.1) discusses the legal binding force of corban vows in detail; the rabbis were aware of the problem Jesus identifies and attempted to create release mechanisms (a rabbi could annul certain vows), but the problem was real. A person could effectively disinherit their parents while maintaining the appearance of exceptional piety.</p>',
    "12": '<p>"Then you no longer let them do anything for their father or mother" — the result is specified: once corban has been invoked, the religious-legal system supports the vow over the fifth commandment\'s obligation. The person who declared corban could not then change their mind without religious-legal release; and even if they did not actually deliver the property to the temple, the declaration created legal cover for denying parents financial support. The Pharisees\' position was apparently that the vow, once made, must be honored — even against parental claims. Jesus\'s point is that this makes the oral tradition the mechanism of the written Torah\'s nullification.</p>',
    "13": '<p>"You nullify the word of God by your tradition that you have handed down" — the word <em>akyrountes</em> (nullify, make void, deprive of authority) is a strong legal term appearing in the LXX for the annulment of agreements and covenants. The oral tradition that was supposed to protect and implement the written Torah has become, in this instance, its nullification. "And you do many things like that" — Jesus indicates that corban is not an isolated case but an instance of a pattern. The systemic nature of the problem means the example is representative, not exceptional; the indictment is structural, not a single-incident complaint.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The shift to "the crowd" for the purity teaching signals a move from a private controversy with the Pharisees to a public declaration. "Listen to me, everyone, and understand this" — the call to attention (<em>akousate mou pantes kai synete</em>) is the standard formula for a wisdom saying or prophetic pronouncement that requires careful hearing. Jesus is about to make a statement that will overturn a fundamental assumption of the purity system — the idea that ritual impurity flows from outside to inside through eating forbidden food — and he addresses it to the widest audience present.</p>',
    "15": '<p>"Nothing outside a person can defile them by going into them. Rather, it is what comes out of a person that defiles them" — in the Levitical framework, ritual impurity flowed from outside to inside: unclean animals or contact with unclean persons made the eater or the touched person impure. Jesus\'s statement reverses the direction: the source of real defilement is the interior of the human person, not external contamination. This does not abolish the Levitical food laws as such (the text does not say that), but it relocates the category of "defilement" from the ritual-physical to the moral-spiritual register.</p>',
    "16": '<p>Mark 7:16 ("If anyone has ears to hear, let them hear") is absent from the earliest and most important manuscripts (Codex Sinaiticus, Codex Vaticanus, and other early witnesses) and is widely recognized as a scribal addition, inserted by copyists to complete the pattern of ear-sayings familiar from 4:9 and 4:23. The verse was almost certainly not in Mark\'s original text; the MKT text at this verse reflects the textually uncertain state of the verse.</p>',
    "17": '<p>The "house" setting for private instruction is a consistent Markan pattern: public teaching addresses crowds in parables or declarative statements; private instruction in the house addresses the disciples\' incomprehension (cf. 4:10, 9:28, 9:33, 10:10). "His disciples asked him about this parable" — Jesus\'s saying about inside/outside defilement is called a parable (<em>parabolē</em>), indicating that it is indirect speech requiring interpretation. The disciples, despite being insiders, need the explanation that the crowd did not receive.</p>',
    "18": '<p>"Are you so dull?" (<em>houtōs kai hymeis asynetoi este</em> — "are you also without understanding?") — the rebuke to the disciples is sharper in Mark than in Matthew (15:16). "Don\'t you see that nothing that enters a person from the outside can defile them?" — the Levitical food system was built on the premise that ingesting unclean food communicated impurity to the person. Jesus is challenging not the authority of the Torah but the premise of how defilement works: dietary laws protected Israelite distinctiveness but did not produce or prevent the fundamental moral condition that "defiles" in the deeper sense.</p>',
    "19": '<p>"For it doesn\'t go into their heart but into their stomach, and then out of the body" — the anatomical argument distinguishes where food goes (stomach → out) from where moral defilement occurs (the heart). Mark adds the editorial comment: "In saying this, Jesus declared all foods clean" (<em>katharizōn panta ta brōmata</em>). This parenthetical interpretation is Mark\'s own — the most significant editorial intervention in the Gospel. It addresses directly the question of Gentile food practices that was a live controversy in the early Gentile church (cf. Acts 10:9-16; Rom 14; Gal 2:11-14). Mark\'s Roman audience needed to know this ruling applied to them.</p>',
    "20": '<p>"What comes out of a person is what defiles them" — the principle being illustrated is the reversal of the defilement-direction from the Levitical system. The Levitical system was not wrong (it served Israel\'s holiness and distinctiveness in the covenant), but Jesus locates fundamental defilement in the interior rather than exterior. The list that follows (vv.21-22) is a vice catalog — a common form in both Jewish wisdom literature (Prov 6:16-19) and Hellenistic moral philosophy (the Stoic list of vices). The catalog\'s function is to make the interior source of defilement concrete and recognizable to both Jewish and Gentile audiences.</p>',
    "21": '<p>The vice catalog begins with "evil thoughts" (<em>dialogismoi hoi kakoi</em>) as the source from which subsequent vices flow — the point is not simply that people do bad things but that bad actions originate in a corrupted interior. The sequence that follows is organized roughly around the second table of the Decalogue (murder, adultery, theft) but expands far beyond it. Sexual immorality (<em>porneiai</em> — plural, a range of sexual violations), theft, and murder are the first three — the actions that most directly violate the rights of others and carry the most serious legal consequences in both Jewish and Roman law.</p>',
    "22": '<p>The continuation of the vice catalog: greed (<em>pleonexiai</em> — the drive to always have more), malice (<em>ponēriai</em> — general wickedness), deceit (<em>dolos</em> — cunning treachery), lewdness (<em>aselgeia</em> — shameless licentiousness), envy (<em>ophthalmos ponēros</em>, "evil eye" — a term for envy or avarice in Semitic idiom), slander (<em>blasphēmia</em>), arrogance (<em>hyperēphania</em> — overweening pride, the Greek hubris equivalent), and folly (<em>aphrosynē</em> — moral stupidity, the opposite of wisdom). The list is not primarily theological but moral-anthropological: a realistic portrait of the human interior without God\'s transformation.</p>',
    "23": '<p>"All these evils come from inside and defile a person" — the conclusion restates the principle of vv.15 and 20. The cumulative vice list is the demonstration: the sources of what actually ruins human community, corrupts relationships, and separates people from God are not foods that enter the body from outside but the interior dispositions that generate the actions cataloged. The Levitical system addressed real concerns (Israel\'s distinctiveness and holiness), but it could not address this interior problem — which is why Jesus\'s teaching here points toward what only the new covenant (Jer 31:33) can accomplish: the law written on the heart.</p>',
    "24": '<p>Tyre was one of the great Phoenician port cities on the Mediterranean coast (modern Lebanon), predominantly Gentile in population. Jesus "entered a house and did not want anyone to know it" — the same withdrawal motif as 7:17 and 9:30. The geographic extension beyond Jewish territory into Tyre continues the Gentile-territory pattern established in the Decapolis (ch.5) and will extend further through Sidon (7:31) and back through the Decapolis to Caesarea Philippi (8:27). These journeys into Gentile territory are not accidental — they pattern the reach of the eventual Gentile mission. The inability to remain hidden confirms the fame that preceded him even across ethnic and religious boundaries.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A woman comes immediately (<em>euthys</em>) upon hearing of him — the word "immediately" appears throughout Mark to convey urgency. "Fell at his feet" (<em>prosepesen pros tous podas autou</em>) is the same gesture of submission used by Jairus (5:22) and the Gerasene demoniac (5:6). Her daughter had an "unclean spirit" (<em>pneuma akatharton</em>) — the same terminology used for the Capernaum (1:23) and Gerasene (5:2) exorcisms. The healing request is made across ethnic, cultural, and geographic lines: a Gentile woman bringing her possessed daughter to a Jewish teacher in Gentile territory.</p>',
    "26": '<p>"The woman was a Greek, born in Syrian Phoenicia" — <em>Hellēnis</em> means Greek-speaking, Gentile (not necessarily of Greek ethnic origin); in first-century usage it was the standard term for non-Jews in a Jewish context (as in Gal 3:28, "neither Jew nor Greek"). Syrian Phoenicia (<em>Syrophoinikissa</em>) was the Roman province of Syria-Phoenicia, distinguishing it from Libyan Phoenicia (the area around Carthage). The double identification — Hellēnis ethnically/culturally, Syrophoenician by regional origin — establishes her unambiguous Gentile status. She makes her request in Greek across the cultural divide.</p>',
    "27": '<p>"First let the children eat all they want, for it is not right to take the children\'s bread and toss it to the dogs" — "children" in this context refers to Israel (cf. Exod 4:22, Hos 11:1); "dogs" was a Jewish idiom for Gentiles, reflecting the social separation between Jew and Gentile in Palestinian culture. Jesus uses <em>kynaria</em> (little dogs, puppies) rather than <em>kynes</em> (dogs in general) — the diminutive slightly softens the term while still using it. The exchange tests whether she will accept a place in the sequence (Israel first) or reject the interaction entirely. Her response shows she accepts the framework and finds her place within it.</p>',
    "28": '<p>"Lord, even the dogs under the table eat the children\'s crumbs" — her reply is exact: she does not contest the priority of Israel ("the children") but argues from within the framework Jesus established. The <em>kynaria</em> (puppies) under the table are part of the household, not outsiders — they receive what falls from the family table as a matter of course, without displacing the children\'s meal. The image is domestic and specific: a Hellenistic household with children eating at table and small dogs underfoot. Her argument concedes the point and finds space within it. In an honor-culture context, this is a rhetorically skilled response that acknowledges hierarchy without abdicating need.</p>',
    "29": '<p>"For such a reply, you may go; the demon has left your daughter" — the healing is granted on the basis of her response. This is the only place in the Gospels where Jesus explicitly grants a request because of the quality of the argument offered. The phrase "for this word" (<em>dia touton ton logon</em>) identifies the reply itself as the ground of the healing. The healing occurs at a distance and without physical contact — paralleling the centurion\'s servant (Matt 8:13), both Gentile healings performed remotely; the absence of physical contact perhaps reflecting the purity boundaries that direct touch would have crossed.</p>',
    "30": '<p>The woman returns home and finds the child "lying on the bed" and the demon gone — the precision of the image (lying calmly, contrast with the Gerasene demoniac\'s unrestrained activity) signals restoration to normalcy. The healing has been accomplished during the conversation: the time when Jesus said "the demon has left your daughter" corresponds to when the healing actually occurred. Mark reports no follow-up, no messianic secret command in Gentile territory (consistent with the pattern of 5:19-20 where Jesus commissioned proclamation rather than silence in the Decapolis).</p>',
    "31": '<p>The route "through Sidon, down to the Sea of Galilee and into the region of the Decapolis" is geographically extensive (Sidon is north of Tyre; going through Sidon to reach the Decapolis means going north before going southeast — a lengthy arc through Gentile territory). The routing takes Jesus through a substantial circuit of predominantly Gentile population centers before returning to the eastern shore of the Sea of Galilee. The cumulative effect is to place Jesus in extended contact with Gentile populations before the feeding of four thousand (8:1-10) in the same territory — the Gentile arc of ministry is systematic.</p>',
    "32": '<p>A deaf-mute man is brought to Jesus in the Decapolis — Gentile territory. "Could hardly talk" (<em>mogilalos</em> — speaking with difficulty) is a rare word that appears in Isaiah 35:6 LXX ("the tongue of the mute will shout for joy"), one of the signs of the eschatological restoration. The healing thus activates an Isaiah-35 fulfillment in Gentile territory. The request to "place his hand on him" is the standard healing gesture of imposition of hands — the community accompanying the man knows what kind of intervention they are requesting, and they intercede for him in the same way Jairus did for his daughter.</p>',
    "33": '<p>Jesus takes the man aside privately, away from the crowd — a deliberate separation consistent with the Messianic Secret pattern, but here the privacy serves a different function: it removes the spectacular from public gaze and makes the healing a personal encounter rather than a performance. The physical techniques — fingers in the ears, spitting and touching the tongue — follow the general pattern of healing acts in the ancient world (Greco-Roman healers also used saliva, which was believed to have healing properties; Tacitus records Vespasian using saliva to heal a blind man at Alexandria). Jesus works within recognizable healing conventions while transforming their effect.</p>',
    "34": '<p>"Ephphatha!" is Aramaic (<em>ethpatah</em>, from the root <em>patah</em>, "to open"), preserved in transliteration here as at 5:41 (<em>talitha koum</em>) and 14:36 (<em>abba</em>). This preservation of Aramaic words is consistent with the Petrine tradition Mark records: eyewitness memory retains the specific syllables spoken, which Mark then transliterates and translates for his Gentile audience. Jesus also "looked up to heaven and with a deep sigh (<em>estenaxen</em>)" — the sigh or groan suggests a prayer or an expression of engagement with the man\'s condition, not a magical incantation. The combination of gesture, physical action, prayer, and word is the full range of healing in Mark.</p>',
    "35": '<p>The healing is immediate and complete: ears opened, tongue loosened, speech clear (<em>orthōs</em> — correctly, plainly). Isaiah 35:5-6 had predicted that in the age of eschatological restoration "the eyes of the blind will be opened, the ears of the deaf unstopped... the tongue of the mute will shout for joy." Jesus\'s healings of the deaf (7:35), the blind (8:25, 10:52), and the mute (7:35) systematically enact these Isaiah-35 signs — and in this case the healing occurs in Gentile Decapolis territory, suggesting that the restoration Isaiah envisioned reaches beyond Israel\'s ethnic boundaries.</p>',
    "36": '<p>The Messianic Secret instruction ("don\'t tell anyone") fails immediately: "the more he did so, the more they kept talking about it." The failure of the Messianic Secret in Gentile territory mirrors its failure in Jewish territory (1:44-45) — the news cannot be contained once healings of this magnitude occur. Mark notes the pattern without apologizing for it: Jesus commands silence, the command is disobeyed, and the disobedience spreads the news further. The Secret is not about effective information management but about preventing premature Messianic enthusiasm before Jesus has defined what kind of Messiah he is through the passion predictions of ch.8-10.</p>',
    "37": '<p>"He has done everything well" (<em>kalōs panta pepoiēken</em>) — the Greek phrase echoes Genesis 1:31 LXX (<em>kala lian</em>, "very good"), where God surveys the finished creation and evaluates it as entirely good. The Gentile crowd in Decapolis is making an inadvertent theological statement: what Jesus does in healing and restoration is "very good" in the same sense that God\'s original creation was very good. "He even makes the deaf hear and the mute speak" extends the Isaiah-35 fulfillment to Gentile recognition — the nations witness the signs of Israel\'s eschatological restoration and name it as entirely good work.</p>'
  },
  "8": {
    "1": '<p>The second feeding takes place in the Decapolis — Gentile territory — during what Mark describes as "those days," linking it temporally to the Syrophoenician woman and deaf-mute healing sequence of ch.7. The structural parallel with the first feeding (6:35-44) is exact: remote location, hungry crowd, disciples\' puzzlement, inadequate provisions, Jesus\'s blessing and distribution, satisfaction with surplus. The differences are significant: five loaves → seven, twelve baskets (<em>kophinos</em>, a Jewish food basket) → seven baskets (<em>spyris</em>, a Gentile wicker basket), five thousand → four thousand. The parallel structure with different numbers invites comparison: the feedings are related but not identical events for related but not identical communities.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"I have compassion for these people; they have already been with me three days and have nothing to eat" — the three days without food signals persistent, determined presence: these Gentile Decapolis crowds have not come for a brief encounter but have stayed through deprivation. Jesus\'s compassion (<em>splanchnizomai</em> — a visceral, gut-level response, the same word used in the first feeding, 6:34) is triggered by sustained commitment. The Gentile crowd has demonstrated the same persistence that Mark praises elsewhere (the Syrophoenician woman\'s argument, Bartimaeus\'s refusal to be silenced): they have stayed when it cost them something.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"Some of them have come a long distance" — the Decapolis region was geographically dispersed (the ten cities stretched from Damascus in the north to Philadelphia/Amman in the south). People drawn from this wide area to follow Jesus for three days represent a remarkable response from predominantly Gentile populations. The practical concern about people collapsing on the way home ("they will faint," <em>eklythēsontai</em>) is not merely pastoral sentimentality but a realistic assessment: people who have gone three days without food and then face a long return journey are at genuine physical risk. The feeding is a humanitarian response to a real logistical crisis.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"But where in this remote place can anyone get enough bread to feed them?" — the disciples\' puzzlement is structurally identical to their question at the first feeding (6:37), and they ask it after having witnessed the feeding of five thousand. The repetition is deliberate: the disciples have failed to transfer learning from the previous miracle. Mark will make this failure explicit in 8:14-21, where Jesus directly confronts their inability to understand the significance of both feedings. Their question is not stupidity but the hardness of heart that prevents carrying learning from one encounter to the next — the same hardness of heart Jesus will diagnose in v.17.</p>',
    "5": '<p>Seven loaves — compared to five in the first feeding. The number seven in Jewish symbolic arithmetic often represented completeness or the world (seven days of creation, seven Gentile nations of Canaan, the seventy nations of the table of nations in Genesis 10). Whether Mark intends the seven to carry explicit symbolic weight for the Gentile feeding is debated, but the difference from the first feeding\'s five loaves is deliberate and noted. The disciples count what they have; Jesus begins the work of provision with what is available, not with what the apparent need requires.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The four eucharistic actions — took, gave thanks (<em>eucharistēsas</em>, from which "Eucharist" derives), broke, gave — are performed here as in 6:41 (where the word was <em>eulogēsen</em>, blessed) and at the Last Supper (14:22-23). The action pattern (taking bread, blessing/giving thanks, breaking, distributing) is the standard Jewish table blessing pattern (<em>berakah</em>). Its appearance at both feedings and the Last Supper creates a triple resonance: the two wilderness feedings and the institution of the Supper all share the same liturgical structure, inviting the reader to see them as part of one continuous act of Jesus as host and provider.</p>',
    "7": '<p>"They had a few small fish as well; he gave thanks for them also" — the fish are secondary to the bread but receive the same thanksgiving. The word for "giving thanks" (<em>eucharistēsas</em>) appears again, reinforcing the eucharistic register. The two-part blessing (bread first, then fish) mirrors the structure of both feedings: bread is the primary element, fish the supplement. The fish in both feedings connect to the disciples\' identity as former fishermen and to the setting on the shores of the Sea of Galilee, even as the crowd is predominantly Gentile in this instance.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The seven basketfuls of leftovers use the word <em>spyris</em> (a large wicker basket, different from the <em>kophinos</em> of 6:43). The distinction is lexically significant: the first feeding\'s leftovers fill twelve Jewish-style food baskets; the second feeding\'s leftovers fill seven Gentile-style wicker baskets. The word <em>spyris</em> appears elsewhere in the NT only in Acts 9:25, where Paul is lowered in a <em>spyris</em> from the Damascus wall — a Hellenistic urban context. Mark\'s specificity about basket type (retained and remembered even in the disciples\' recall at 8:19-20) is consistent with eyewitness detail preserved by Peter.</p>',
    "9": '<p>About four thousand people — the number is lower than the five thousand of the first feeding, and the text does not add "men only" as in 6:44, which may suggest the count includes all persons present. The dismissal of the crowd follows the pattern of 6:45: Jesus sends the crowd away after the feeding, without ceremony or extended teaching. The transition from feeding to boat-crossing is immediate. The departure for Dalmanutha brings Jesus back into contact with Jewish religious authorities who apparently monitored his movements across the lake.</p>',
    "10": '<p>Dalmanutha — the location is uncertain; Matthew\'s parallel (15:39) names Magadan (or Magdala, a town on the western shore near Tiberias). The geographical movement from the eastern Decapolis shore to the western (Jewish) shore brings Jesus back into contact with the Pharisees. The contrast between the Gentile crowd that had no bread and stayed three days and the Pharisees who immediately "come and begin to question" highlights the different orientations of the two groups toward Jesus: one sought nourishment; the other seeks confrontation and validation of their own authority over him.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The Pharisees demand "a sign from heaven" (<em>sēmeion apo tou ouranou</em>) — not just a miracle (which they had presumably heard about) but a specifically celestial, unambiguous divine authentication. The phrase "from heaven" echoes the Exodus manna: Moses had given bread from heaven (Exod 16; cited in John 6:31) as the defining miracle of his prophetic ministry. The Pharisees are implicitly demanding Moses-caliber heavenly attestation before they will acknowledge Jesus\'s authority. The request comes immediately after two wilderness feedings — the typological irony is sharp: the sign they demand is exactly what he has already been doing.</p>',
    "12": '<p>Jesus "sighed deeply" (<em>anastenaxas tō pneumati</em> — an intensive construction: sighed deeply in his spirit) — the most emotionally charged description of Jesus\'s response in Mark. "Why does this generation ask for a sign?" "This generation" (<em>hē genea hautē</em>) is the OT prophetic phrase for Israel in its season of unbelief (Deut 32:5,20; Ps 95:10; cf. Mark 9:19). "Truly I tell you, no sign will be given to it" — the refusal is absolute. Those who demand a sign before believing have already decided against belief; a sign will not change the decision but merely become the next basis for further skepticism.</p>',
    "13": '<p>Jesus leaves them — the departure is a definitive response to the sign-demand by withdrawal. He gets back into the boat and crosses to the other side. The crossing is one of many in Mark (4:35, 5:1, 5:21, 6:45, 8:10, 8:13), each marking a transition between Jewish and Gentile territory or between phases of ministry. The pattern in Mark is consistent: when those who should receive him reject him, Jesus moves on to those who receive him. The Pharisees\' confrontation ends with Jesus simply leaving, having refused their terms and not proposed alternative ones.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The disciples forgot to bring bread — having just participated in two mass feedings, they are crossing the lake with only one loaf between them. The absurdity is deliberate. Mark records the detail precisely: one loaf (<em>hena arton</em>), in the boat with them. Jesus uses this as an occasion for a teaching about "the yeast of the Pharisees and that of Herod" — the disciples immediately interpret his metaphorical warning through the lens of their bread shortage rather than hearing it as a warning about something entirely different. Their material preoccupation colonizes their hearing.</p>',
    "15": '<p>"Watch out for the yeast of the Pharisees and that of Herod" — yeast (<em>zymē</em>) in Jewish usage was often a metaphor for corruption or influence that spreads invisibly through a whole lump (cf. 1 Cor 5:6-8; Gal 5:9, where Paul uses the same metaphor). The Pharisees\' "yeast" in context is the demand for signs (v.11) and the underlying disposition of bad faith and testing. Herod\'s "yeast" is the political pragmatism and compromised fear that led to John\'s execution (6:20-26). Both represent forms of corruption that prevent genuine encounter with Jesus\'s person and teaching.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The disciples\' internal discussion — "it is because we have no bread" — demonstrates the literal-mindedness that Jesus is about to rebuke. They are applying the word "yeast" to the physical bread situation and concluding that Jesus is warning them about some problem with their insufficient provisions. They have imported the material concern of the moment into the metaphorical teaching and come out with a misreading. This failure of interpretive understanding — hearing Jesus\'s words through the lens of immediate material preoccupation — is the precise problem that the two feedings should have addressed but apparently have not resolved.</p>',
    "17": '<p>"Why are you talking about having no bread? Do you still not see or understand? Are your hearts hardened?" — the triple question escalates: the first is practical, the second is perceptual, the third is diagnostic. "Hardened hearts" (<em>pepōrōmenēn</em> — perfect passive participle of <em>pōroō</em>, to petrify/harden) is the same language used of Pharaoh in the Exodus narrative and of Israel in Isaiah 6:10. It was applied to the disciples after the first feeding (6:52: "they had not understood about the loaves; their hearts were hardened"). Now, after the second feeding, the same condition is diagnosed. The disciples are experiencing what Isaiah prophesied about Israel.</p>',
    "18": '<p>"Do you have eyes but fail to see, and ears but fail to hear?" — the citation echoes Jeremiah 5:21 and Ezekiel 12:2, both of which use this language for Israel\'s spiritual blindness during the exile period. Mark has already introduced the eyes/ears theme through the Isaiah 6:9-10 citation in 4:12 (why Jesus teaches in parables). Now the disciples themselves are being indicted with the language used for Israel\'s hardness of heart. The coming healing of the blind man (8:22-26) and the confession at Caesarea Philippi (8:27-30) will show whether the diagnosis is permanent or temporary.</p>',
    "19": '<p>"When I broke the five loaves for the five thousand, how many basketfuls of pieces did you pick up?" "Twelve." — Jesus recounts both feedings in sequence, citing the specific numbers: twelve <em>kophinoi</em> from the first feeding and seven <em>spyrides</em> from the second. The different basket words are preserved in the recall, confirming that the distinction was intentional and memorable. The numbers are being interrogated as signs: twelve and seven are not mere surplus accounting but potentially encoded meaning. If the disciples can remember the numbers but not understand what they signified, their problem is not memory but interpretation — they see without perceiving.</p>',
    "20": '<p>"And when I broke the seven loaves for the four thousand, how many basketfuls of pieces did you pick up?" "Seven." — the recitation of both feeding-accounts with their precise numbers (5 loaves / 12 baskets and 7 loaves / 7 baskets) is a structured memory exercise: recall the event, recall the numbers, now understand the pattern. The passage ends without Jesus providing the interpretation ("Do you still not understand?" v.21). The interpretation is left open — structurally appropriate since the healing of the blind man (vv.22-26, a two-stage miracle) and Peter\'s partial confession at Caesarea Philippi (8:29) are themselves the beginning of the disciples\' partial sight that requires further healing.</p>',
    "21": '<p>"Do you still not understand?" (<em>oupō syniete</em>) — the question is left unanswered in Mark, hanging in the air as the boat arrives at Bethsaida. The unresolved question creates the narrative space into which the two-stage healing of the blind man (8:22-26) is inserted as a visual parable: just as the blind man first sees people "like trees walking" (partially, but distorted) before seeing clearly, so the disciples understand partially but distortedly before they can see Jesus clearly. The structural placement of the Bethsaida healing immediately after the blindness-accusation is deliberate and interpretive — the narrative itself provides the answer.</p>',
    "22": '<p>Bethsaida — a fishing village on the northeastern shore of the Sea of Galilee, the hometown of Philip, Andrew, and Peter (John 1:44). Philip the tetrarch elevated it to a city and named it Julias (after Julia, daughter of Augustus) ca. 2 BCE (Josephus, Ant. 18.28). A blind man is brought; the community intercedes for him with the same verb (<em>parakalein</em>, to beg/implore) used for the Syrophoenician woman\'s request (7:26) and Jairus\'s (5:23). Communal intercession for the one who cannot help himself is a consistent pattern in Mark\'s healing accounts.</p>',
    "23": '<p>Jesus leads the blind man out of the village by hand — a private healing, removed from the crowd, consistent with the pattern of 7:33. The spitting on the eyes and imposition of hands is the physical technique of healing; saliva was considered medically therapeutic in the ancient world (Pliny, Natural History 28.4; Tacitus, Histories 4.81, where Vespasian uses saliva to heal a blind man; the Tosefta also notes therapeutic use of saliva). The question after the first action — "Do you see anything?" — is unique in the Gospel tradition: no other healing of Jesus is recorded as occurring in stages with an interim question about results.</p>',
    "24": '<p>"I can see people; they look like trees walking around" — the first stage of sight produces a distorted image: human beings perceived as tree-like forms in motion. The image is precise and phenomenologically real: someone experiencing gradual return of vision after blindness might perceive forms before detail, movement before identity. Trees were the largest vertical objects familiar to a Galilean; people moving at a distance, to someone with partial sight, might look like large trees walking. The partial perception is not failure but the first stage of a process — and it is a precise image of what the disciples are doing with Jesus: seeing something real but without sufficient clarity to identify it correctly.</p>',
    "25": '<p>Jesus puts his hands on the man\'s eyes again — a second stage of the same healing. The eyes are opened (<em>dieneblepen</em> — a compound intensive form, "saw through clearly"), sight is restored, and he saw "everything clearly" (<em>tēlaugōs panta</em> — the adverb <em>tēlaugōs</em> means "brilliantly clearly," used only here in the NT). The two-stage healing is the only recorded instance in the Gospels of a miracle requiring a second intervention. Its structural position — between the disciples\' blindness accusation (8:18) and Peter\'s partial sight at Caesarea Philippi (8:29-30) — makes it a narrative parable: the disciples\' spiritual perception is real but not yet clear, requiring further work by Jesus.</p>',
    "26": '<p>"Don\'t even go into the village" — a stricter form of the Messianic Secret instruction than usual (don\'t return to the place you came from, not just don\'t tell anyone). The instruction keeps the healing entirely private. In contrast to the deaf-mute healing where the command to silence immediately failed (7:36), here Mark records no failure — the man presumably complied. The Bethsaida private healing stands as a quiet counterpoint to the public proclamation that follows at Caesarea Philippi (8:27ff): what happens privately in Bethsaida (partial sight becoming clear) is what needs to happen publicly among the disciples.</p>',
    "28": '<p>The popular identifications of Jesus — John the Baptist raised from the dead (Herod\'s conclusion, 6:16), Elijah (expected before the Day of the LORD per Mal 4:5, debated in rabbinic literature), or one of the prophets (the general expectation of prophetic restoration in the last days, Deut 18:15-18) — reflect the available categories of Jewish eschatological thought. All three are figures of returning or continuing divine-prophetic activity. None of them is adequate: John was Jesus\'s forerunner, not Jesus himself; Elijah is not the Messiah; the category "one of the prophets" is too general to name what the disciples are encountering.</p>',
    "29": '<p>"You are the Messiah" (<em>Su ei ho Christos</em>) — Peter\'s answer uses <em>Christos</em>, the Greek translation of the Hebrew <em>Mashiach</em> (Anointed One), the title for the expected Davidic king. The confession is correct in its title but, as immediately becomes apparent (vv.31-33), Peter\'s understanding of what "Messiah" means is wrong: he expects a triumphant Davidic king, not a crucified Servant. The immediate command to silence (v.30) follows — telling no one "about him" — because a correct title attached to a wrong content would be more dangerous than no title at all. A publicly acclaimed Messiah-king would trigger the political movement Jesus was not leading.</p>',
    "30": '<p>"Jesus warned them not to tell anyone about him" — the Messianic Secret at its most emphatic. The reason is structural: in Jewish popular expectation, "Messiah" meant a Davidic warrior-king who would overthrow Rome and restore Israel\'s political sovereignty. A public announcement that Jesus is the Messiah would trigger precisely this expectation and set in motion a political movement Jesus was not leading. The passion prediction that follows immediately (v.31) begins to redefine the category: this Messiah must suffer and be killed and rise. The title can only be announced when its content has been established by the cross.</p>',
    "31": '<p>"The Son of Man must suffer many things and be rejected by the elders, the chief priests and the teachers of the law, and that he must be killed and after three days rise again" — the first passion prediction. The word <em>dei</em> (must, it is necessary) signals divine necessity — this is not a tragic accident but the pattern God has ordained. The three groups named (elders, chief priests, scribes) are precisely the membership of the Sanhedrin, the Jerusalem supreme council with capital jurisdiction. The prediction of being "killed and rising after three days" is stated plainly (<em>parrēsia</em>, openly), removing any ambiguity. The disciples\' failure to receive it (v.32) is not a failure of comprehension but of acceptance.</p>',
    "32": '<p>Peter "took him aside and began to rebuke him" — the verb <em>epitiman</em> (rebuke) is the same word used for Jesus\'s exorcism commands (1:25, 3:12) and his stilling of the storm (4:39). Peter is applying the authority gesture of exorcism to Jesus — treating Jesus\'s passion prediction as a malevolent speech that must be silenced. The presumption is staggering: the disciple who just confessed Jesus as Messiah now treats Jesus\'s own interpretation of his messianic mission as something to be rebuked away. Peter cannot reconcile "Messiah" with "suffering and death" — and he has enough relationship with Jesus to believe he can correct him privately.</p>',
    "33": '<p>"Get behind me, Satan! You do not have in mind the concerns of God, but merely human concerns" — Jesus turns and faces the other disciples while addressing Peter: the rebuke is public, not private. "Satan" (<em>Satana</em>) — the word means "adversary" in Hebrew; in the OT, the satan is one who opposes, blocks, or accuses (Job 1-2; Zech 3:1). Peter, by opposing the divine plan for the suffering Messiah, is functioning as the Adversary — the one who works against God\'s purpose. The diagnostic contrast is sharp: "concerns of God" (<em>ta tou theou</em>) vs. "human concerns" (<em>ta tōn anthrōpōn</em>). Peter is thinking exactly as the world thinks about power, triumph, and how God should act in history.</p>',
    "34": '<p>"Whoever wants to be my disciple must deny themselves and take up their cross and follow me" — the cross-bearing saying was spoken to "the crowd" as well as the disciples: this is not esoteric teaching for insiders only. For Mark\'s Roman audience, "taking up one\'s cross" was not a metaphor — it was a familiar sight. Condemned criminals in the Roman world carried the horizontal beam (<em>patibulum</em>) of their cross to the place of execution, walking publicly through the city as a deterrent display. The audience hearing Jesus say this would have seen crucifixion processions. The call to discipleship is a call to publicly identify with someone on the way to death — with all the social and physical consequences that implies in a Roman context.</p>',
    "35": '<p>"For whoever wants to save their life will lose it, but whoever loses their life for me and for the gospel will save it" — the paradox operates on the Greek word <em>psychē</em>, which can mean life (biological), soul (the self), or both simultaneously. The saying reverses normal self-preservation logic: clinging to life (protecting oneself from the cross) results in ultimate loss; surrendering life (for Jesus and the gospel) results in ultimate preservation. For a community facing the Neronian persecution (the probable context of Mark\'s writing, ca. 65-70 CE), this was not abstract theology but a real decision about whether to deny Christ or confess him under threat of death.</p>',
    "36": '<p>"What good is it for someone to gain the whole world, yet forfeit their soul?" — the question uses commercial language: <em>kerdainō</em> (gain) is the word for commercial profit; <em>zēmiōthē</em> (forfeit, suffer loss) is the word for commercial loss. The exchange rate is the issue: the entire world\'s resources on one side of the ledger, the soul (<em>psychē</em>) on the other — and the calculation goes entirely against the world. In the Roman imperial context, "gaining the whole world" was not a purely hypothetical scenario: Roman emperors and generals had done exactly this. The saying implicitly evaluates the Roman imperial achievement as a poor trade by the only accounting that matters.</p>',
    "37": '<p>"Or what can anyone give in exchange for their soul?" (<em>ti gar doi anthrōpos antillagma tēs psychēs autou</em>) — the word <em>antillagma</em> (exchange price, equivalent) appears in the LXX of Psalm 49:8-9 (Ps 48 LXX): "No one can redeem the life of another or give to God a ransom for them — the ransom for a life is costly, no payment is ever enough." The citation activates the Psalm\'s context: the rich man who trusts in wealth cannot buy his way to permanent life. The ransom-language here connects directly to 10:45 ("the Son of Man came... to give his life as a ransom for many"), where Jesus provides what humans cannot.</p>',
    "38": '<p>"If anyone is ashamed of me and my words in this adulterous and sinful generation" — the "adulterous and sinful generation" echoes the OT prophetic charge against Israel for covenant unfaithfulness (the marriage metaphor for Israel\'s relationship with God, in which idolatry is "adultery": Hos 2, Jer 3, Ezek 16). The context of Caesarea Philippi, surrounded by evidence of Roman imperial religion (the Pan grotto, the nearby temple to Augustus), makes "this adulterous generation" refer to those who have accommodated themselves to imperial religion and culture. The Son of Man coming "in his Father\'s glory with the holy angels" is the parousia language of Daniel 7:13-14, casting the coming judgment in explicit Danielic terms.</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'mark')
    merge_comm(existing, MARK)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'mark', existing)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    print(f'Mark mkt-context chs 7-8: {total} verses total written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
